[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 14.3: Python Implementation Example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simplified, illustrative implementation of the inventory reorder optimization from Recipe 14.3. It demonstrates the core concepts (problem formulation, constraint definition, solver invocation, solution interpretation) using an open-source MIP solver. It is not production-ready. The item catalog is tiny, the demand model is static, and there's no ERP integration. Think of it as the whiteboard sketch that helps you understand the shape of the real system. A starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > The main recipe uses ECS Fargate for the solver and SageMaker for demand forecasting. This example runs everything locally with the HiGHS solver (via the `highspy` Python bindings) and hardcoded demand parameters. The optimization math is identical; the infrastructure is stripped away so you can focus on the model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You'll need the optimization solver and AWS SDK installed:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3 highspy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m `highspy` is the Python interface to HiGHS, an open-source linear and mixed-integer programming solver. It's fast, well-maintained, and handles the problem sizes typical of hospital inventory optimization (thousands of items) without a commercial license.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs AWS credentials configured (via environment variables, instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:PutItem`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:GetItem`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:Query`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:PutObject`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:GetObject`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For the full pipeline (with demand forecasting), you'd also need `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, but this example uses hardcoded demand parameters to keep the focus on the optimization itself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Configuration and Constants
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import math
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import logging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import datetime
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from datetime import timezone
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from decimal import Decimal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import highspy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from botocore.config import Config
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger.setLevel(logging.INFO)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG = Config(retries={"max_attempts": 3, "mode": "adaptive"})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m dynamodb = boto3.resource("dynamodb", config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Service level targets by criticality tier.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # These represent the probability of NOT stocking out during a replenishment cycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Critical items (crash cart meds, blood products): 99.5% fill rate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Essential items (surgical supplies, common meds): 98%.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Standard items (office supplies, non-urgent consumables): 95%.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SERVICE_LEVELS = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "critical": 0.995,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "essential": 0.98,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "standard": 0.95,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Z-scores from the standard normal distribution corresponding to each service level.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # safety_stock = z * standard_deviation_of_demand_during_lead_time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Z_SCORES = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     0.995: 2.576,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     0.98: 2.054,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     0.95: 1.645,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Annual holding cost rate: percentage of unit cost per year to hold one unit in inventory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # 25% is typical for healthcare (capital cost + storage + insurance + obsolescence).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ANNUAL_HOLDING_RATE = 0.25
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Fixed cost per purchase order (administrative processing, receiving, etc.).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ORDERING_COST_PER_ORDER = 50.00
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Solver time limit in seconds. For large catalogs, the solver may not prove
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # optimality within this window but will return the best solution found.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SOLVER_TIME_LIMIT_SECONDS = 300
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
